@@eThe Eccentric Woodland@@N

The Eccentric Woodland is @@yMidgaard's@@N southern pressure-valve
frontier: a nearby forest that never fully accepted city law, yet
never fully escaped city influence. It orbits Midgaard without
belonging to it.

Travelers leaving the Southern Wild Gate expect a conventional
transition: city wall, patrol road, outer farms, then wild canopy.
Instead, the Woodland presents inconsistency. Clearings feel pastoral
for an hour and @@rpredatory by dusk@@N. Old game paths move or close
between visits. Isolated halls and burrows are maintained by groups
with their own ritual authority.

Before Midgaard's southern districts were paved, the land beyond the
ninth milestone was a fog-prone verge navigated by @@dshepherd-priests
and bell walkers@@N who guided the lost through hollows. When the
Lantern Reforms attempted to standardize southern routes, survey
clerks entered the label "Eccentric Woodland" into civic usage -- a
registry convenience admitting the area's irregular behavior while
still assigning it a ledger category.

Patrol reports from every era note the same failures: path drift,
contradictory witness accounts, and landmarks that cannot be found
on follow-up inspections. Midgaard's practical response has always
been bureaucratic rather than military: keep the gate records clean,
classify interior incidents as variance events, and maintain plausible
governance at the edge.

Four social forces contest the interior. @@gPath Wardens@@N sell
navigation and protection along claimed routes. @@dRitual Houses@@N --
enclosed groups using oath language and symbolic spaces -- legitimate
rank through dueling rooms, binding circles, and ceremony. @@rPredator
Bands@@N mimic ritual forms to induce fear and compliance. @@ySurvivor
Clusters@@N inhabit burrows and clearings as temporary barter points.

None fully controls the Woodland. Power is local, contingent, and
often theatrical. The forest demonstrates what happens when Midgaard's
core doctrine -- @@yorder as infrastructure@@N -- is applied only at
boundaries. Roads no longer reliably return to watched squares.
Posted notices cannot stabilize terrain that resists repeatable
pathing. Registry systems lose force where witnesses are scarce.

The Woodland persists as an institutional blind spot everyone can
point to and no office can absorb.
